article.description: Another steady night for Karl Malone and John Stockton, and another winning season for the Utah Jazz.

Utah Jazz coach Jerry Sloan suspended
reserve center John Amaechi for Friday's game against the
Sacramento Kings after the two had a heated exchange late in a victory over the Los Angeles Clippers.

article.headline: Jazz deliver blow to Clippers' playoff hopes
article.linkText: Jazz clinch NBA-record 17th straight winning season
article.story:
SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Ho, hum. Just another day at the office for Karl Malone and John Stockton.
Stockton

Malone

Yawn. Another winning season for the Utah Jazz. Malone had 24 points, eight rebounds and seven assists, and Stockton added 11 points and nine assists as the Utah Jazz beat the Los Angeles Clippers 99-87 Wednesday night. The Mailman said the formula hasn't changed after playing 17 seasons with Stockton. With the two future Hall of Famers running the plays, it's teamwork that moves a clockwork offense and makes the Jazz successful. "You let the game be easy," Malone said. "If guys are double-teaming me, that means you get a wide-open shot or a layup if you keep it simple." The Jazz opened their lead over the Clippers for the eighth and final playoff Western Conference playoff spot to five games. Even better for Utah, seventh-place Seattle lost in San Antonio and the Jazz moved a half-game behind the Sonics. The Jazz are 2½ games behind Portland for the No. 6 spot. "We're not settling on the eighth spot," Donyell Marshall said. "We're right up there for the seventh spot and maybe even the sixth. We've still got a lot of games left and we're trying to move up as far as we can." The Jazz beat the Clippers for the 26th straight time in Salt Lake City and the 14th straight overall. Los Angeles coach Alvin Gentry was asked why Utah has been so successful against his team. "I'll give you two reasons," he said. "No. 12 and No. 32. I'll bet if you go back and look, there's a direct correlation, and it's not just us. They've won 50 games it seems like forever." The Jazz have won six of their last eight and this victory assured them of a 17th straight winning season, an NBA record. Utah was tied with the Los Angeles Lakers at 16 straight, which the Lakers did from 1976-77 to 1991-92. Elton Brand had 24 points and 11 rebounds for the Clippers, moving within one game of Swen Nater's franchise record of 54 double-doubles set in 1980-81, but the Clips didn't get much beyond Brand. "We're not good enough if we don't play together," Gentry said. Corey Maggette, making his first start since returning from a 16-game absence with a dislocated right foot, scored 18 but all in the second half when the game was out of reach. Bryon Russell scored 13 points and Andrei Kirilenko had nine of his 17 points in the third quarter, when Utah oustscored Los Angeles 32-25. The Clippers had a horrible third quarter, missing eight of their first 10 shots from the field. "We played good defense, got out in the open floor and guys were very active with good hands," Stockton said. "That gave us some easy chances." Kirilenko had five points during a decisive 10-0 run, capping it with a drive and reverse dunk over Darius Miles to force a Los Angeles timeout. That didn't slow Utah, which used a 10-3 run over the next 4 minutes to make it 67-39. "We tried to be confident and concentrate on the game, and we played as a team," Kirilenko said. "We passed to each other, not holding the ball and it was good for us because we were a real team." Game notes
Clippers forward Lamar Odom didn't travel with the squad. A team spokesman said he will have surgery on a sprained ligament in his right wrist but no date has been set. ... The Clippers haven't beaten the Jazz since March 27, 1999. They haven't won in Salt Lake City since April 18, 1989. ... Jazz guard DeShawn Stevenson turned 21, one week and a day after Stockton turned 40.
